{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566283","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566283"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:38:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:38:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18783"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18783"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.2,0.15,0.03,0.58]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11516"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78608"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11516"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18783"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63950"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"432"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"8800"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26828"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39848"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78608"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with gradual painless blurring of vision in her right eye over three months. She describes waves in her central vision.  She has a 15-year history of type 2 diabetes mellitus with known diabetic retinopathy, hypertension, and dyslipidaemia. Her medications include metformin, gliclazide, perindopril, and atorvastatin. Her most recent glycated haemoglobin (HbA1c) is 75 mmol/mol (42-48).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her visual acuity is 6/18 in the right eye and 6/6 in the left eye. Fundoscopy reveals retinal thickening and exudates in the right macula. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management of the most likely condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical prednisolone drops","Observation and glycaemic control only","Pan-retinal photocoagulation","Oral acetazolamide","Intravitreal anti-VEGF injection"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with diabetic macular oedema (DMO) causing significant visual impairment, as evidenced by reduced visual acuity and confirmed by OCT findings. When DMO affects central vision (visual acuity worse than 6/12), prompt treatment is essential to prevent permanent vision loss.  Fluid accumulates in the macula disrupting retinal architecture and causing oedema and retinal cell death.  As macular oedema can be caused by different reasons, treatment is targeted at the individual causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravitreal anti-VEGF injection\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard first-line treatment for centre-involving DMO. Anti-VEGF agents such as aflibercept, ranibizumab, or bevacizumab work by reducing vascular permeability and angiogenesis. Multiple studies have shown their effectiveness in improving vision and reducing macular thickness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical prednisolone drops\u003C/strong\u003E would not penetrate sufficiently to treat macular oedema secondary to diabetic mellitus. While intravitreal steroids can be effective for DMO, they are typically reserved for cases that are refractory to anti-VEGF therapy due to their side effect profile, including cataract formation and increased intraocular pressure, and more commonly used for non-infectious uveitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral acetazolamide\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used for cystoid macular oedema following cataract surgery or failed corticosteroid terhapy, but is not indicated for diabetic macular oedema. It would not address the underlying pathophysiology of DMO.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPan-retinal photocoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat proliferative diabetic retinopathy but is not the appropriate treatment for macular oedema. In fact, it can sometimes worsen macular oedema if performed in isolation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation and glycaemic control\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient given the degree of visual impairment. While optimising systemic factors (including blood glucose, blood pressure, and lipids) is important, it should be done in conjunction with specific treatment for the macular oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intravitreal anti-VEGF therapy is first-line treatment for diabetic macular oedema affecting central vision.","Optical Coherence Tomography (OCT) is essential for diagnosing and monitoring macular oedema.","Visual acuity of 6/12 or worse is a key threshold for initiating treatment in diabetic macular oedema."],"references":["Haydinger CD, Ferreira LB, Williams KA, Smith JR. Mechanisms of macular edema. Front Med (Lausanne). 2023.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10027768/","Mitchell P, Wong T. Management Paradigms for Diabetic Macular Edema. American Journal of Opthalmology. 2014: 157 (3).  Available at:https://www.ajo.com/article/S0002-9394(13)00735-6/abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63950"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18783"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63950"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T18:41:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T18:42:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11516"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78608"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags